21
00:02:19,227 --> 00:02:19,868
[SPEAKER_11]: The meeting is called to order.

22
00:02:19,888 --> 00:02:20,991
[SPEAKER_11]: Please rise to salute the flag.

23
00:02:34,345 --> 00:02:45,748
[SPEAKER_11]: Announcements, accolades, remembrances, reports, and records 26096 offered by President Behrs be it resolved by the Medford City Council that we offer condolences to the family and friends of Mimi Gordon and commemorate her life.

24
00:02:46,388 --> 00:02:56,411
[SPEAKER_11]: Mimi was a long-time member of the Medford Democratic City Committee and Ward 8 Democratic Committee, tireless union representative with SEIU 509, public servant, campaign worker, and party activist.

25
00:02:56,851 --> 00:02:59,652
[SPEAKER_11]: She was a beloved member of the Medford community, and we will miss her.

26
00:03:00,732 --> 00:03:01,772
[SPEAKER_11]: Any councilors want to speak?

27
00:03:03,373 --> 00:03:03,973
[SPEAKER_11]: Councilor Singh.

28
00:03:06,228 --> 00:03:08,250
[SPEAKER_04]: Mimi was a true leader in our community.

29
00:03:09,371 --> 00:03:14,715
[SPEAKER_04]: She's one of the first people who I met when I was campaigning for this position.

30
00:03:14,915 --> 00:03:20,039
[SPEAKER_04]: And through her knowledge, experience, her passion, I've learned so much.

31
00:03:20,099 --> 00:03:28,446
[SPEAKER_04]: And I think counselors, I don't want to speak for everyone, but I'm sure counselors abound will say that they have learned so much.

32
00:03:30,917 --> 00:03:46,256
[SPEAKER_04]: We've been able to do a lot, and I think what people don't necessarily always see is that behind the things we do as a city council, there's always a community, and there's always people who are driving the effort, who are making us do better.

33
00:03:47,120 --> 00:03:52,965
[SPEAKER_04]: making us learn about issues, making us better counselors too.

34
00:03:53,225 --> 00:03:54,867
[SPEAKER_04]: And Mimi was one of those people.

35
00:03:56,028 --> 00:03:57,068
[SPEAKER_04]: She'll be dearly missed.

36
00:03:57,909 --> 00:04:01,952
[SPEAKER_04]: And I want to just convey my deepest condolences.

37
00:04:03,814 --> 00:04:04,875
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you, Councilor Sang.

38
00:04:04,935 --> 00:04:05,576
[SPEAKER_11]: Councilor Lemming.

39
00:04:06,857 --> 00:04:09,879
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you, Council President, for this resolution.

40
00:04:09,919 --> 00:04:12,521
[SPEAKER_10]: So I'll say that I

41
00:04:15,542 --> 00:04:23,790
[SPEAKER_10]: I didn't know Mimi too well myself, but I know a lot of people who knew her and were influenced her through the Ward 8 Democratic Committee.

42
00:04:24,430 --> 00:04:33,479
[SPEAKER_10]: She spent over 20 years organizing that committee, recruiting members across the ward and really

43
00:04:35,781 --> 00:04:41,906
[SPEAKER_10]: revitalizing it in the long time that she spent as committee chair.

44
00:04:42,306 --> 00:04:49,732
[SPEAKER_10]: And a lot of the folks, a lot of folks reached out to me about this.

45
00:04:50,093 --> 00:04:53,496
[SPEAKER_10]: And to echo my colleague, councilor saying,

46
00:04:55,257 --> 00:05:03,987
[SPEAKER_10]: are so many people who add so much to the scene by what they do behind the scenes.

47
00:05:04,208 --> 00:05:14,259
[SPEAKER_10]: There's like any anytime you see political organization, anytime you see city councilors, anytime you see, you know, people that are sort of in front of the crowd giving speeches.

48
00:05:15,120 --> 00:05:29,125
[SPEAKER_10]: is there are even more people who quietly do the work of recruiting people talking to them one on one organizing and Mimi was a person who did that in spades over a very, very long period of time.

49
00:05:29,686 --> 00:05:35,088
[SPEAKER_10]: And so it's no surprise to me that she touched so many people within a

50
00:05:35,948 --> 00:05:39,550
[SPEAKER_10]: uh, within the Democratic Party, especially, especially here in Medford.

51
00:05:39,830 --> 00:05:43,352
[SPEAKER_10]: So, uh, thank you again for this, for this resolution.

52
00:05:43,392 --> 00:05:45,413
[SPEAKER_10]: And this was, this was a real loss to our community.

53
00:05:47,475 --> 00:05:48,515
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you, Councilor Lemming.

54
00:05:48,535 --> 00:05:56,900
[SPEAKER_11]: Um, Mimi was someone who I've known for, um, maybe more than 10 years.

55
00:05:57,600 --> 00:06:00,362
[SPEAKER_11]: And I think, you know, she represents

56
00:06:02,110 --> 00:06:05,373
[SPEAKER_11]: some of the most important values that we could have as a community.

57
00:06:05,573 --> 00:06:12,639
[SPEAKER_11]: She's a kind person, a principled person, a passionate person, and an engaged person.

58
00:06:12,759 --> 00:06:27,331
[SPEAKER_11]: She was very devoted to the labor movement, to unions and workers, to local politics, to thinking globally, acting locally,

59
00:06:29,919 --> 00:06:53,427
[SPEAKER_11]: And more than anything, she was just someone that you really enjoyed talking to, whether it was about things going on here in Medford, or things going on state, federal politics, local state Democratic Party, or just her love for her family, her friends, her community, and the people around her.

60
00:06:53,547 --> 00:06:54,288
[SPEAKER_11]: I think she had a...

61
00:06:58,877 --> 00:07:01,179
[SPEAKER_11]: She believed in people.

62
00:07:01,319 --> 00:07:04,141
[SPEAKER_11]: She believed in the human spirit.

63
00:07:04,221 --> 00:07:08,845
[SPEAKER_11]: And I think she fought very hard to just try to help her fellow neighbor.

64
00:07:09,165 --> 00:07:17,052
[SPEAKER_11]: And she certainly inspired me on more than one occasion to maybe

65
00:07:18,043 --> 00:07:25,467
[SPEAKER_11]: speak a little louder or fight a little harder or talk to someone who maybe I hadn't considered talking to before.

66
00:07:25,947 --> 00:07:29,429
[SPEAKER_11]: And I've missed her actually already these past couple of years.

67
00:07:29,629 --> 00:07:36,353
[SPEAKER_11]: She's had some health issues and to lose her is a major loss for our community.

68
00:07:36,553 --> 00:07:43,717
[SPEAKER_11]: So I'm thankful for everything she did, for all the people that she influenced, for all the people that she lifted up.

69
00:07:44,497 --> 00:07:46,739
[SPEAKER_11]: and that we can celebrate her tonight.

70
00:07:46,759 --> 00:07:50,463
[SPEAKER_11]: And I know there's some folks here who maybe wanna say a few words about Mimi as well.

71
00:07:50,623 --> 00:07:57,950
[SPEAKER_11]: So we will turn the floor over to members of the public now who might wanna share a few words about Mimi Gordon.

72
00:08:14,588 --> 00:08:16,589
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm Barry Ingber, 9 Draper Street.

73
00:08:17,870 --> 00:08:21,892
[SPEAKER_12]: And I was a friend of Mimi's for over 40 years.

74
00:08:22,392 --> 00:08:26,855
[SPEAKER_12]: And she was a very committed and kind person.

75
00:08:28,135 --> 00:08:31,377
[SPEAKER_12]: She was both gentle and fierce.

76
00:08:32,658 --> 00:08:41,282
[SPEAKER_12]: And she built community wherever she went, at every level, from her condo to the labor union to the city of Medford to the Democratic Party.

77
00:08:44,075 --> 00:09:03,504
[SPEAKER_12]: I think as people have intimated, she's the kind of person who I think many people in the community will miss without even knowing that we miss her because she accomplished a lot very quietly.

78
00:09:05,405 --> 00:09:05,765
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you.

79
00:09:07,626 --> 00:09:08,007
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

80
00:09:09,847 --> 00:09:12,749
[SPEAKER_11]: Is there anyone else who'd like to speak at this time about me?

81
00:09:17,563 --> 00:09:18,103
[SPEAKER_11]: Seeing none.

82
00:09:18,123 --> 00:09:22,686
[SPEAKER_11]: Oh, we have someone on Zoom.

83
00:09:22,926 --> 00:09:25,067
[SPEAKER_11]: I will recognize Munir Jermanis.

84
00:09:31,130 --> 00:09:34,252
[SPEAKER_15]: Munir Jermanis, Three Summits Road.

85
00:09:35,853 --> 00:09:41,676
[SPEAKER_15]: I met Mimi primarily through people power.

86
00:09:43,533 --> 00:09:54,419
[SPEAKER_15]: She was, as everybody mentioned, a quietly active, gentle individual, a woman of principle.

87
00:09:55,860 --> 00:09:58,801
[SPEAKER_15]: And I, for one, will certainly miss her presence.

88
00:09:59,442 --> 00:09:59,802
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

89
00:10:01,663 --> 00:10:02,103
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

90
00:10:06,405 --> 00:10:08,527
[SPEAKER_11]: And I'll recognize now Matt Sampson on Zoom.

91
00:10:08,627 --> 00:10:11,148
[SPEAKER_11]: Matt, name and address for the record, please.

92
00:10:13,868 --> 00:10:17,453
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, I'm Matt Sampson, 131 Winchester Street, Brookline.

93
00:10:17,473 --> 00:10:18,675
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm Mimi Gordon's nephew.

94
00:10:19,436 --> 00:10:29,990
[SPEAKER_05]: I moved to Boston seven years ago and only got to know Mimi over the past seven years with the depth that many of you have known her for years and decades.

95
00:10:30,993 --> 00:10:35,215
[SPEAKER_05]: The past couple of years, as some of you have alluded to, were somewhat difficult for Mimi.

96
00:10:35,355 --> 00:10:39,057
[SPEAKER_05]: Her world became smaller as she lost some physical mobility.

97
00:10:39,757 --> 00:10:46,261
[SPEAKER_05]: But I want to assure those folks listening on Zoom and those of you here representing Medford that she thought about you often.

98
00:10:46,901 --> 00:10:59,950
[SPEAKER_05]: the issues that she brought to the floor over the decades, the fights that she fought were still deep within her, and she valued a civic discourse, the political process, and all of you members of the Medford Council.

99
00:11:00,190 --> 00:11:07,455
[SPEAKER_05]: And I just want to thank you for giving her a place, a community, and an outlet for the vast amounts of energy she had over decades.

100
00:11:08,075 --> 00:11:10,937
[SPEAKER_05]: She set a real role model, a role model for

101
00:11:11,997 --> 00:11:21,805
[SPEAKER_05]: her family, her nieces, her nephews, and now her little grandnieces and nephews, Lily, age 17, Addie, age two, Arlo, eight months.

102
00:11:22,405 --> 00:11:32,974
[SPEAKER_05]: They knew an aunt who, while small and somewhat diminished physically, was strong and bright and a role model for those of us who want to participate in civic discourse.

103
00:11:33,014 --> 00:11:33,614
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you very much.

104
00:11:36,116 --> 00:11:37,217
[SPEAKER_11]: Matt, thank you so much.

105
00:11:37,297 --> 00:11:38,938
[SPEAKER_11]: And our condolences to your family.

106
00:11:39,479 --> 00:11:40,800
[SPEAKER_11]: And may her memory be a blessing.

107
00:11:45,336 --> 00:11:47,196
[SPEAKER_11]: We'll take a vote and then we'll take a moment of silence.

108
00:11:47,296 --> 00:11:48,377
[SPEAKER_11]: Is there a motion to approve?

109
00:11:50,017 --> 00:11:54,298
[SPEAKER_11]: On the motion of Councilor Callahan to approve, seconded by Vice President Lazaro.

110
00:11:54,338 --> 00:11:55,338
[SPEAKER_11]: Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

111
00:11:57,218 --> 00:11:58,019
[SPEAKER_08]: Councilor Callahan?

112
00:11:58,039 --> 00:11:58,099
[SPEAKER_08]: Yes.

113
00:11:59,499 --> 00:12:00,179
[SPEAKER_08]: Councilor Lemming?

114
00:12:00,779 --> 00:12:01,079
[SPEAKER_08]: Yes.

115
00:12:02,299 --> 00:12:02,860
[SPEAKER_08]: Councilor Mullain?

116
00:12:02,880 --> 00:12:02,960
[SPEAKER_08]: Yes.

117
00:12:04,280 --> 00:12:05,040
[SPEAKER_08]: Councilor Scarpelli?

118
00:12:05,060 --> 00:12:05,140
[SPEAKER_08]: Yes.

119
00:12:06,180 --> 00:12:06,800
[SPEAKER_08]: Councilor Singh?

120
00:12:06,820 --> 00:12:06,880
[SPEAKER_08]: Yes.

121
00:12:07,881 --> 00:12:08,721
[SPEAKER_08]: Vice President Lazaro?

122
00:12:08,761 --> 00:12:08,821
[SPEAKER_08]: Yes.

123
00:12:09,601 --> 00:12:10,201
[SPEAKER_08]: President Beers?

124
00:12:10,401 --> 00:12:10,661
[SPEAKER_11]: Yes.

125
00:12:10,781 --> 00:12:12,161
[SPEAKER_11]: Seven in the affirmative, none in the negative.

126
00:12:12,181 --> 00:12:13,222
[SPEAKER_11]: The motion passes.

127
00:12:13,282 --> 00:12:14,542
[SPEAKER_11]: Please rise for a moment of silence.

128
00:12:39,780 --> 00:12:40,200
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

129
00:12:43,563 --> 00:12:59,493
[SPEAKER_11]: Paper 26097 offered by Vice President Lazaro, whereas first responders and veterans are disproportionately affected by mental health disorders including PTSD, anxiety and depression and whereas many first responders and veterans can feel uncomfortable reaching out for help with mental health concerns.

130
00:13:00,540 --> 00:13:08,582
[SPEAKER_11]: due to negative stigma, often instead turning to substances and whereas people with substance use disorder also face significant negative stigma in this community and elsewhere.

131
00:13:08,722 --> 00:13:19,364
[SPEAKER_11]: Now, therefore, be it resolved that the Medford City Council discuss and promote the important work of Medford's recovery coach, Chris Summa, who is now offering a regular weekly recovery meeting for first responders and veterans dealing with substance use disorder.

132
00:13:19,825 --> 00:13:23,365
[SPEAKER_11]: This meeting takes place at the First Baptist Church of Medford every Tuesday at 7 p.m.

133
00:13:23,845 --> 00:13:30,167
[SPEAKER_11]: Be it further resolved that the city council invite Chris and Director of Veterans Services, Victoria Shaw, to the May 26th meeting to discuss and promote the recovery group.

134
00:13:30,695 --> 00:13:31,636
[SPEAKER_11]: Vice President Lazaro.

135
00:13:33,617 --> 00:13:34,397
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you very much.

136
00:13:35,978 --> 00:13:41,701
[SPEAKER_13]: I would invite the two leaders of this group who have worked really hard to put this together.

137
00:13:41,721 --> 00:13:47,164
[SPEAKER_13]: This is a group that meets.

138
00:13:47,224 --> 00:13:50,906
[SPEAKER_13]: It's open to anybody who would like to partake of the services.

139
00:13:52,007 --> 00:13:55,208
[SPEAKER_13]: Chris Summa has been here at city council meetings a few times before.

140
00:13:57,257 --> 00:13:59,960
[SPEAKER_13]: I appreciate any opportunity to have him come back.

141
00:14:01,462 --> 00:14:06,067
[SPEAKER_13]: Director Shah has been also present for a number of occasions.

142
00:14:06,368 --> 00:14:09,452
[SPEAKER_13]: I understand your speech at the Memorial Day celebration.

143
00:14:09,472 --> 00:14:09,992
[SPEAKER_13]: I couldn't make it.

144
00:14:10,012 --> 00:14:10,373
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm sorry.

145
00:14:10,393 --> 00:14:13,797
[SPEAKER_13]: It was very lovely and happy to have you here again.

146
00:14:16,551 --> 00:14:24,696
[SPEAKER_13]: The, so recovery groups are like an unaffiliated kind of AA meeting, but you don't have to do anything specific.

147
00:14:24,736 --> 00:14:29,759
[SPEAKER_13]: It's just talking about your place in recovery where you're at.

148
00:14:30,540 --> 00:14:41,907
[SPEAKER_13]: And Chris put together this group specifically for people who are veterans or first responders and in that, having that in common with each other.

149
00:14:43,291 --> 00:14:46,696
[SPEAKER_13]: can allow people to feel more comfortable sharing about their experiences.

150
00:14:46,816 --> 00:14:56,328
[SPEAKER_13]: So rather than me speaking for you, I just wanted to give you an opportunity to come and tell us and the public about this group and give you an opportunity to

151
00:14:58,401 --> 00:15:01,663
[SPEAKER_13]: sort of talk more about it and let people know how they can join.

152
00:15:01,823 --> 00:15:09,208
[SPEAKER_13]: Also, incidentally, just today I received my email and I saw that it was on Facebook, too, that the mayor's office put out a press release, which is really cool.

153
00:15:09,769 --> 00:15:12,311
[SPEAKER_13]: And so it's on, you know, a lot of different channels.

154
00:15:12,391 --> 00:15:15,032
[SPEAKER_13]: So, you know, I hope you're not overrun tonight.

155
00:15:15,273 --> 00:15:16,634
[SPEAKER_13]: I mean, you're not there, unfortunately.

156
00:15:16,834 --> 00:15:18,155
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm sorry we ran an hour over.

157
00:15:18,175 --> 00:15:18,975
[SPEAKER_13]: You probably could have been.

158
00:15:20,236 --> 00:15:21,517
[SPEAKER_13]: So thank you for coming.

159
00:15:22,117 --> 00:15:27,441
[SPEAKER_13]: Please, I would love through the chair to invite you to speak about the group and how it's been going.

160
00:15:28,902 --> 00:15:30,604
[SPEAKER_11]: Thanks, Chris and Veronica.

161
00:15:30,864 --> 00:15:31,665
[SPEAKER_11]: Sorry, go ahead.

162
00:15:31,705 --> 00:15:38,813
[SPEAKER_00]: So I'm going to just kind of give you a little bit of background on how we got to here, and then I'll turn it over to Chris to give you all of the details.

163
00:15:39,374 --> 00:15:46,122
[SPEAKER_00]: So the group actually came about because you'll know that one of my biggest passions is working on homeless veterans.

164
00:15:47,590 --> 00:15:59,421
[SPEAKER_00]: And doing my research, discovered that one of the biggest causes for veterans to become homeless is substance abuse and other disorders, substance disorders.

165
00:15:59,441 --> 00:16:05,806
[SPEAKER_00]: And the push within the veterans community is how do we deal with there?

166
00:16:05,846 --> 00:16:07,368
[SPEAKER_00]: Do we deal with the substance abuse first?

167
00:16:07,388 --> 00:16:10,410
[SPEAKER_00]: Do we deal with the homelessness first?

168
00:16:10,430 --> 00:16:12,292
[SPEAKER_00]: And there's really no good solution.

169
00:16:14,906 --> 00:16:17,327
[SPEAKER_00]: For me, I want to do both.

170
00:16:17,927 --> 00:16:23,708
[SPEAKER_00]: So I've already spoken with you guys about the initiatives I'm doing to help end veteran homelessness here in Medford.

171
00:16:24,208 --> 00:16:28,269
[SPEAKER_00]: But then we have to address the issues of substance abuse.

172
00:16:28,769 --> 00:16:32,490
[SPEAKER_00]: How do we prevent veterans from needing the other services?

173
00:16:32,830 --> 00:16:34,711
[SPEAKER_00]: We have to address it at the root cause.

174
00:16:35,711 --> 00:16:37,211
[SPEAKER_00]: And that's where Chris comes in.

175
00:16:37,351 --> 00:16:40,612
[SPEAKER_00]: I approached him, said, hey, let's team up.

176
00:16:40,772 --> 00:16:43,533
[SPEAKER_00]: So many of our first responders are veterans.

177
00:16:43,573 --> 00:16:44,673
[SPEAKER_00]: They go hand in hand.

178
00:16:45,774 --> 00:17:00,684
[SPEAKER_00]: Let's create a group here in Medford for anybody, any veteran, any first responder from any city, they need some place to just go and talk with their brothers and sisters about whatever is bothering them, just getting through the day.

179
00:17:01,865 --> 00:17:04,446
[SPEAKER_00]: From my own personal experience working with the VA,

180
00:17:05,267 --> 00:17:13,352
[SPEAKER_00]: There's a lot of groups, but when you come in and you're not an older veteran or male, there's really not much out there.

181
00:17:14,413 --> 00:17:22,198
[SPEAKER_00]: It was very uncomfortable for me to sit in groups with men who were twice my age, didn't have my same experiences.

182
00:17:22,278 --> 00:17:26,161
[SPEAKER_00]: They had their own amazing service experiences, but they weren't the same.

183
00:17:26,221 --> 00:17:27,522
[SPEAKER_00]: They're different generations.

184
00:17:28,222 --> 00:17:30,364
[SPEAKER_00]: And I wanted to create something here

185
00:17:31,783 --> 00:17:36,924
[SPEAKER_00]: for my generation of veteran, for the younger generation of veterans.

186
00:17:37,984 --> 00:17:40,925
[SPEAKER_00]: That's how Chris comes in, because he's the expert.

187
00:17:40,965 --> 00:17:46,886
[SPEAKER_00]: So I'll let him tell you how we formed the group, what's going to happen, and everything else.

188
00:17:48,726 --> 00:17:49,106
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you.

189
00:17:49,506 --> 00:17:50,266
[SPEAKER_18]: I appreciate that.

190
00:17:51,786 --> 00:17:53,347
[SPEAKER_18]: So just a little back story on me.

191
00:17:53,527 --> 00:17:58,728
[SPEAKER_18]: Before I got into recovery work, I worked in law enforcement for a little over 10 years.

192
00:18:01,008 --> 00:18:09,893
[SPEAKER_18]: I found that I was unable to talk about the issues that we face on a regular basis, and there wasn't a safe outlet for that.

193
00:18:10,613 --> 00:18:15,155
[SPEAKER_18]: And getting into recovery work, first responders were always near and dear to my heart.

194
00:18:15,676 --> 00:18:17,477
[SPEAKER_18]: As soon as I met Veronica, it was like,

195
00:18:18,471 --> 00:18:19,452
[SPEAKER_18]: the perfect storm.

196
00:18:19,692 --> 00:18:22,213
[SPEAKER_18]: We came together and it just made sense.

197
00:18:23,614 --> 00:18:31,558
[SPEAKER_18]: I personally went through McLean Hospital, the detox program, and they have a program there called the LEADER program, which is designed for first responders.

198
00:18:32,118 --> 00:18:39,962
[SPEAKER_18]: And there was a meeting that they had in Belmont, and they used to call it a badge meeting, and it was first responders, veterans.

199
00:18:40,322 --> 00:18:42,543
[SPEAKER_18]: And it was the only time that I really felt at home.

200
00:18:43,143 --> 00:18:44,064
[SPEAKER_18]: When I got out of there,

201
00:18:44,704 --> 00:18:48,907
[SPEAKER_18]: Getting to Belmont was an issue, especially early in recovery.

202
00:18:49,387 --> 00:18:53,049
[SPEAKER_18]: You take travel time, you take people that may not have vehicles, transportation.

203
00:18:53,650 --> 00:18:54,450
[SPEAKER_18]: It's tough to get there.

204
00:18:54,470 --> 00:18:57,292
[SPEAKER_18]: You're looking three, four hours to get back and forth for a meeting.

205
00:18:57,572 --> 00:18:59,593
[SPEAKER_18]: And in early recovery, it's difficult.

206
00:19:01,479 --> 00:19:06,642
[SPEAKER_18]: When we started talking about this, as you guys know, I run the recovery group, which is an all recovery group on Wednesdays.

207
00:19:06,722 --> 00:19:07,543
[SPEAKER_18]: Anybody can attend.

208
00:19:08,043 --> 00:19:13,727
[SPEAKER_18]: And we said it would be great if we had something close by, something that's T accessible, something that everybody can get to.

209
00:19:13,747 --> 00:19:15,788
[SPEAKER_18]: It doesn't matter what your zip code is.

210
00:19:16,148 --> 00:19:16,688
[SPEAKER_18]: You're welcome.

211
00:19:17,449 --> 00:19:22,672
[SPEAKER_18]: And it's for all former and current military veterans, first responders.

212
00:19:23,733 --> 00:19:26,775
[SPEAKER_18]: And it's titled a recovery group.

213
00:19:27,395 --> 00:19:34,000
[SPEAKER_18]: But realistically, it's a safe place where people can come and dump whatever they're holding inside on the table.

214
00:19:34,600 --> 00:19:39,423
[SPEAKER_18]: And maybe in those moments, you wouldn't burn your life to the ground like I did.

215
00:19:39,803 --> 00:19:42,525
[SPEAKER_18]: If I had an outlet like that, maybe things would have been different.

216
00:19:42,906 --> 00:19:49,570
[SPEAKER_18]: Because the stuff that we see, even other groups that I attend, I can't talk about with other people.

217
00:19:50,010 --> 00:19:51,591
[SPEAKER_18]: I'm gonna use the phrase civilians.

218
00:19:52,172 --> 00:19:56,375
[SPEAKER_18]: But I can't talk about it with civilians because we're put in situations where we see

219
00:19:57,615 --> 00:19:58,476
[SPEAKER_18]: intense things.

220
00:19:58,556 --> 00:20:00,256
[SPEAKER_18]: We do intense things.

221
00:20:00,777 --> 00:20:04,199
[SPEAKER_18]: Things that regular people may look at and shake their heads at.

222
00:20:04,819 --> 00:20:15,485
[SPEAKER_18]: At the group that we run, when I say something that has to do with my past or experiences that I've had, when I look around the room, everybody's nodding their head yes.

223
00:20:15,845 --> 00:20:17,466
[SPEAKER_18]: They understand where I'm coming from.

224
00:20:17,886 --> 00:20:21,268
[SPEAKER_18]: So yes, we do offer support for substance use disorder.

225
00:20:22,329 --> 00:20:24,250
[SPEAKER_18]: But we offer support for anybody that

226
00:20:25,219 --> 00:20:30,981
[SPEAKER_18]: has served, is serving, that can benefit from a safe place to talk all of your problems out.

227
00:20:31,061 --> 00:20:37,163
[SPEAKER_18]: It doesn't matter if it's PTSD, it doesn't matter if it's alcohol, it doesn't matter if it's drugs, it makes no difference.

228
00:20:37,663 --> 00:20:38,883
[SPEAKER_18]: It's just having an outlet.

229
00:20:39,423 --> 00:20:47,506
[SPEAKER_18]: And I just wanna say, we've actually, we've started it the beginning of this month, and we have a good core group of people.

230
00:20:48,966 --> 00:20:53,448
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you so much for letting us come and present, because getting the word out is,

231
00:20:54,608 --> 00:20:55,888
[SPEAKER_18]: Everything right now.

232
00:20:55,928 --> 00:21:13,593
[SPEAKER_18]: What's running based on where the mouth but with the press release and everything that's happening really excited to see where it can take us this is it's just great for for anybody that can benefit from this and As you all know like substance use disorder and mental health disorder it touches all of us and sometimes

233
00:21:14,859 --> 00:21:20,021
[SPEAKER_18]: people think that because you're wearing a uniform, because you're serving, it doesn't affect you.

234
00:21:20,421 --> 00:21:22,082
[SPEAKER_18]: It does, because we're people first.

235
00:21:22,642 --> 00:21:26,944
[SPEAKER_18]: The jobs that we do and the positions that we hold, they don't give us extra strength.

236
00:21:27,484 --> 00:21:33,706
[SPEAKER_18]: We're supposed to have extra strength, and that's what's drilled into us, but it doesn't mean that you can't talk about things.

237
00:21:33,746 --> 00:21:35,947
[SPEAKER_18]: It doesn't mean that we don't bleed just like everybody else.

238
00:21:36,487 --> 00:21:39,788
[SPEAKER_18]: So this is just a safe outlet for people to come, talk, get support.

239
00:21:40,509 --> 00:21:40,889
[SPEAKER_18]: The group,

240
00:21:41,844 --> 00:21:51,029
[SPEAKER_18]: is running a supportive nature in terms of, you know, if you bring something up and somebody else has, you know, a similar situation in the group, we offer advice, we offer support.

241
00:21:51,329 --> 00:22:04,476
[SPEAKER_18]: So just to give you a quick example, this past meeting that we just had this past week, the topic of conversation, because I'll generally say, you know, does anybody have anything pressing that they wanna discuss tonight?

242
00:22:04,936 --> 00:22:08,518
[SPEAKER_18]: And the topic that was discussed this past week was reaching out for help.

243
00:22:09,218 --> 00:22:11,840
[SPEAKER_18]: So it wasn't even related to substances.

244
00:22:12,000 --> 00:22:14,382
[SPEAKER_18]: It was just the difficulty in reaching out for help.

245
00:22:14,783 --> 00:22:21,308
[SPEAKER_18]: The difficulty in being the person that everybody turns to for help, and now you're the one having to ask for help.

246
00:22:21,828 --> 00:22:32,157
[SPEAKER_18]: And everybody in the group just offered what they do to reach out for help, and it's very supportive, it's very loving, it's very nurturing, and it's just, most importantly, it's a safe space.

247
00:22:32,617 --> 00:22:38,222
[SPEAKER_18]: And the group, as you said, it's every Tuesday night, 7 p.m., First Baptist Church on Oakland Street.

248
00:22:39,463 --> 00:22:44,266
[SPEAKER_18]: And yeah, we're looking forward to, you know, getting this going and getting as many people involved as possible.

249
00:22:44,306 --> 00:22:48,049
[SPEAKER_18]: So thank you for giving us the opportunity to get it out to the public and in front of all of you.

250
00:22:48,089 --> 00:22:49,109
[SPEAKER_18]: We really appreciate that.

251
00:22:49,149 --> 00:22:50,010
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you guys so much.

252
00:22:51,311 --> 00:22:52,112
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you guys so much.

253
00:22:52,192 --> 00:22:53,212
[SPEAKER_11]: It's really appreciated.

254
00:22:57,736 --> 00:23:05,461
[SPEAKER_13]: I appreciate, I have so many things I want to respond to and what you said, but really quick, just your other recovery group is on Wednesday.

255
00:23:05,521 --> 00:23:06,502
[SPEAKER_13]: Is that also at seven?

256
00:23:07,188 --> 00:23:11,333
[SPEAKER_18]: So the Wednesday recovery group is every Wednesday from 4.30 to 5.30.

257
00:23:11,393 --> 00:23:13,335
[SPEAKER_18]: That's an all recovery group.

258
00:23:13,475 --> 00:23:14,556
[SPEAKER_18]: Anybody can attend that.

259
00:23:14,916 --> 00:23:15,457
[SPEAKER_13]: And that's here?

260
00:23:15,877 --> 00:23:17,039
[SPEAKER_18]: It's held right up here in room 201.

261
00:23:18,100 --> 00:23:20,803
[SPEAKER_18]: And we provide pizza, chicken fingers, salad.

262
00:23:21,223 --> 00:23:29,232
[SPEAKER_18]: So we always put it out there as like, you know, come be surrounded by supporting people, like-minded people, get yourself a meal and one heck of a good meeting.

263
00:23:29,592 --> 00:23:30,093
[SPEAKER_13]: That's awesome.

264
00:23:30,313 --> 00:23:48,329
[SPEAKER_13]: Okay, so we have two recovery groups in Medford right now that are run by Chris and I also did want to mention that the homelessness veterans homelessness is a huge problem, but I happen to work with a lot of people that Practice the housing first model.

265
00:23:48,389 --> 00:23:51,752
[SPEAKER_13]: So you do housing and then you manage recovery which can be a

266
00:23:52,208 --> 00:23:59,529
[SPEAKER_13]: really complicated when you're doing mixed housing with people who are in mixed income levels and all walks of life.

267
00:23:59,669 --> 00:24:01,370
[SPEAKER_13]: And there's a lot to manage with that.

268
00:24:01,410 --> 00:24:06,411
[SPEAKER_13]: And then it becomes a really high priority to manage the substance use disorder and maybe mental health issues.

269
00:24:06,511 --> 00:24:11,152
[SPEAKER_13]: So it's really great that you're doing a project like this for people who are local.

270
00:24:11,752 --> 00:24:13,412
[SPEAKER_13]: And I'll give you a second to respond.

271
00:24:14,312 --> 00:24:18,573
[SPEAKER_13]: But the other thing that you mentioned, Chris, about proximity to where people are.

272
00:24:19,694 --> 00:24:31,182
[SPEAKER_13]: in early recovery, how important it is to have access to groups like this or maybe a doctor or a facility where you can go to get the kind of help that you need.

273
00:24:31,462 --> 00:24:37,186
[SPEAKER_13]: So it's just something that I like to repeat and remind people that it is really important to have access to the

274
00:24:38,027 --> 00:24:50,011
[SPEAKER_13]: assistive medications, assistive services, and community groups that can help people when they're in those early stages because that can be the difference between being able to stay in recovery or not.

275
00:24:50,491 --> 00:24:56,053
[SPEAKER_13]: If you have to drive somewhere far away and you're trying to keep your job and you're trying to keep your family together, all that stuff can be really difficult.

276
00:24:56,113 --> 00:25:00,635
[SPEAKER_13]: So anything that we can do to continue helping the people in Medford that need help I think is really important.

277
00:25:01,655 --> 00:25:10,104
[SPEAKER_18]: The one thing I wanted to add to that is, if I'm not mistaken, the T, you take it to Oak Grove, and then there's a bus that takes you right to Medford Square.

278
00:25:10,725 --> 00:25:12,927
[SPEAKER_18]: And literally, it's walking distance from Medford Square.

279
00:25:12,947 --> 00:25:14,549
[SPEAKER_18]: It's like a minute and a half up the street.

280
00:25:14,689 --> 00:25:16,571
[SPEAKER_18]: So anybody can get here.

281
00:25:16,611 --> 00:25:18,553
[SPEAKER_18]: And that's the beauty of where it's located.

282
00:25:18,893 --> 00:25:21,776
[SPEAKER_18]: Where, like I said, when it was in Belmont, getting there was difficult.

283
00:25:21,796 --> 00:25:24,058
[SPEAKER_18]: There's a lot of people that they lose their ability to drive.

284
00:25:25,520 --> 00:25:36,876
[SPEAKER_18]: If now, if you're trying to get there, you're paying a fortune in terms of Uber, or you're asking people for rides, or whatever it is that you're getting there, it's much more difficult.

285
00:25:36,996 --> 00:25:41,903
[SPEAKER_18]: So this is kind of making it much easier for people to get to the help that they so desperately need.

286
00:25:43,124 --> 00:25:49,010
[SPEAKER_00]: I'll say the other reason when we were looking at a location for this group.

287
00:25:49,710 --> 00:25:58,599
[SPEAKER_00]: The most obvious was do it here in City Hall but that's not a safe it's not a safe place for city employees and we wanted to make sure.

288
00:25:59,059 --> 00:26:06,086
[SPEAKER_00]: that it was neutral ground, that there was nobody that was going to be looking over their shoulder to see who was watching.

289
00:26:06,186 --> 00:26:08,048
[SPEAKER_00]: This is neutral territory.

290
00:26:08,088 --> 00:26:16,037
[SPEAKER_00]: It is a safe place for anybody, whether they work for the city, they're a private citizen, that they have someplace to go.

291
00:26:17,550 --> 00:26:19,151
[SPEAKER_18]: That's one other thing I wanted to chime in.

292
00:26:19,191 --> 00:26:28,455
[SPEAKER_18]: Just piggybacking off of what she said, even though I'm the recovery coach for the city of Medford, while I'm facilitating that meeting, what's said in that meeting stays in that meeting.

293
00:26:29,035 --> 00:26:43,221
[SPEAKER_18]: And obviously, unless you say you're gonna hurt yourself or somebody else, whatever's talked about in there, people can come and feel absolutely safe that whatever we talk about stays there because it's about finding a safe space for us to dump what we have inside on the table.

294
00:26:43,921 --> 00:26:44,201
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you.

295
00:26:46,129 --> 00:26:46,749
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you, guys.

296
00:26:47,649 --> 00:26:48,509
[SPEAKER_11]: Really appreciate it.

297
00:26:49,590 --> 00:26:51,850
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you for your work and for the help you're providing.

298
00:26:51,870 --> 00:26:53,791
[SPEAKER_11]: It's really important.

299
00:26:53,951 --> 00:26:54,251
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

