00:44:06,141 --> 00:44:08,001
[SPEAKER_11]: But sure, if, go ahead Lisa.

559
00:44:08,021 --> 00:44:15,543
[SPEAKER_14]: I was going to say, through you, through the chair, I appreciate what you're saying and absolutely like we wait until June

560
00:44:16,043 --> 00:44:20,853
[SPEAKER_14]: We don't have an application right now for an affordable housing opportunity.

561
00:44:25,207 --> 00:44:37,093
[SPEAKER_14]: pass and put it into the affordable housing trust fund, we will, when we have an affordable housing application, we would be able to better fund that application.

562
00:44:37,153 --> 00:44:48,658
[SPEAKER_14]: So what we're trying to do is prepare for affordable housing developers to come into the city of Medford and where there's that gap in the finances that we can be able to assist them.

563
00:44:48,758 --> 00:44:52,720
[SPEAKER_14]: So right now there isn't an application that I'm aware of

564
00:44:53,360 --> 00:44:54,601
[SPEAKER_14]: in front of the board.

565
00:44:55,041 --> 00:45:00,605
[SPEAKER_14]: I do hope to see one in the next fiscal year or sooner.

566
00:45:02,586 --> 00:45:08,810
[SPEAKER_14]: But until then, we're just trying to make sure that when a developer comes to us, because it's a big ask.

567
00:45:08,890 --> 00:45:09,510
[SPEAKER_14]: It's big.

568
00:45:09,710 --> 00:45:20,437
[SPEAKER_14]: We ask for a lot of applications, excuse me, documentation, and we just want to be able to fund the developer should, when they come to us.

569
00:45:22,068 --> 00:45:25,951
[SPEAKER_11]: Yeah, I think June 9th or June 23rd, and we've heard from you what this would be for.

570
00:45:25,971 --> 00:45:30,956
[SPEAKER_11]: I think we just, it sounds like Councilor Scarpelli just wants to consider it in the context of all the other budget over the next month.

571
00:45:32,117 --> 00:45:32,537
[SPEAKER_11]: So.

572
00:45:33,378 --> 00:45:34,779
[SPEAKER_07]: Apples to apples, I would support it.

573
00:45:35,179 --> 00:45:42,065
[SPEAKER_07]: And that's, I just want you to know how, it's a belief in that, what we've been asking for in these initiatives.

574
00:45:43,325 --> 00:45:50,831
[SPEAKER_07]: Unfortunately, the way the world is, we'll say yes to this and then tomorrow we'll get 6,000 phone calls saying that, now you're not going to support this.

575
00:45:50,951 --> 00:45:53,313
[SPEAKER_07]: And it's not fair to everybody.

576
00:45:53,373 --> 00:45:58,558
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that when we know the whole number, I'll gladly support everything together.

577
00:45:58,758 --> 00:46:04,042
[SPEAKER_07]: But right now, I think that she's putting the cart ahead of the horse.

578
00:46:04,983 --> 00:46:06,064
[SPEAKER_07]: But I appreciate you.

579
00:46:06,164 --> 00:46:06,524
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

580
00:46:06,744 --> 00:46:06,925
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

581
00:46:06,965 --> 00:46:09,667
[SPEAKER_11]: I'll recognize Vice President Lazaro and then Councilor Lemming.

582
00:46:11,715 --> 00:46:12,195
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

583
00:46:12,575 --> 00:46:16,357
[SPEAKER_13]: I recognize my colleague's hesitation.

584
00:46:18,257 --> 00:46:23,519
[SPEAKER_13]: It's hard to do regular business when you're being stonewalled in a lot of ways.

585
00:46:24,440 --> 00:46:38,485
[SPEAKER_13]: But for me personally, I feel like it's really important to not let our political conflicts

586
00:46:40,173 --> 00:46:52,276
[SPEAKER_13]: get in the way of the people who need things to work functionally in government right now so that they can move forward with their lives and access the assistance that they need.

587
00:46:52,336 --> 00:46:56,837
[SPEAKER_13]: And I think the Affordable Housing Trust is an example of that, where it's, like, necessary for us to move forward.

588
00:46:57,697 --> 00:47:07,800
[SPEAKER_13]: Though I have full respect and understanding of why my colleague would want to do something differently, and I absolutely can, believe me, understand it.

589
00:47:11,691 --> 00:47:19,324
[SPEAKER_13]: I also think it's really important to spend free cash, and I don't want to do anything that would encourage the holding of money that was

590
00:47:19,962 --> 00:47:28,188
[SPEAKER_13]: budgeted for something that then maybe it was a position that was never filled or and then it became free cash and then you can just, you know, not spend it.

591
00:47:29,309 --> 00:47:30,850
[SPEAKER_13]: So I think it's important to spend free cash.

592
00:47:30,910 --> 00:47:35,573
[SPEAKER_13]: I think it's important for us to fund the Affordable Housing Trust.

593
00:47:35,613 --> 00:47:40,636
[SPEAKER_13]: I think it's important for us to do with that money the work that you all are doing.

594
00:47:41,137 --> 00:47:46,360
[SPEAKER_13]: So I would definitely just want to move forward with this while we have the opportunity.

595
00:47:46,781 --> 00:47:47,001
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

596
00:47:47,535 --> 00:47:48,736
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you, Councillor Lemming.

597
00:47:48,796 --> 00:47:53,960
[SPEAKER_11]: And just because we table it for a week, for one or two meetings, we can approve it at that time.

598
00:47:54,000 --> 00:47:54,981
[SPEAKER_11]: We don't have to reject it.

599
00:47:55,121 --> 00:48:00,345
[SPEAKER_11]: We can just hold it until we get the budget before us and maybe the free cash paper, end of year free cash paper.

600
00:48:01,086 --> 00:48:01,566
[SPEAKER_11]: Councillor Lemming.

601
00:48:02,945 --> 00:48:08,389
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, so I agree with the idea of supporting it now.

602
00:48:08,509 --> 00:48:11,611
[SPEAKER_10]: I completely understand where my colleague is coming from.

603
00:48:11,691 --> 00:48:18,355
[SPEAKER_10]: I think that the timing of this around budget season and a very conflicted one is unfortunate.

604
00:48:18,395 --> 00:48:20,336
[SPEAKER_10]: But a couple of reasons I support it.

605
00:48:20,376 --> 00:48:23,518
[SPEAKER_10]: First, this isn't the mayor asking us to give her money.

606
00:48:23,578 --> 00:48:31,944
[SPEAKER_10]: This is the mayor asking us to put money into the Affordable Housing Trust, which is a board that is run by people who this council confirmed

607
00:48:32,644 --> 00:48:43,474
[SPEAKER_10]: So that's one aspect that gives me a little bit more trust that they'll spend it appropriately, too.

608
00:48:43,974 --> 00:48:45,776
[SPEAKER_10]: As Chair Davidson was saying, it is

609
00:48:48,080 --> 00:49:03,745
[SPEAKER_10]: I don't think the Affordable Housing Trust needs to come along with a plan for exactly how they're going to spend it, because as she was saying, the Affordable Housing Trust by nature kind of does need to be opportunistic with how it spends its money, because affordable housing projects don't come along all that often.

610
00:49:03,805 --> 00:49:06,546
[SPEAKER_10]: So these things could sit around for years and years.

611
00:49:06,566 --> 00:49:13,488
[SPEAKER_10]: You don't spend a penny, and then suddenly an apartment building goes on the market, and you need to be able to have

612
00:49:15,975 --> 00:49:26,998
[SPEAKER_10]: a pile of cash in order to purchase that or to support an affordable housing developer who might want to purchase that for the benefit of citizens.

613
00:49:28,658 --> 00:49:34,340
[SPEAKER_10]: Just given the long-term nature of the Affordable Housing Trust, I don't think that we need to ask them to

614
00:49:35,160 --> 00:49:54,139
[SPEAKER_10]: come up with a specific plan for how it's going to be spent because that that's that that's not really what they what they do and second and third uh the budget is you know it's it's it's the operating budget and I know that my my colleagues are all aware of this but just to clarify for the public you know we have a lot of conflicts

615
00:49:55,120 --> 00:49:56,341
[SPEAKER_10]: over the operating budget.

616
00:49:56,361 --> 00:50:06,025
[SPEAKER_10]: There's historically been a lot of active debate on this council about the nature of potentially spending free cash on operating budgets.

617
00:50:06,946 --> 00:50:14,430
[SPEAKER_10]: And we want clarification from the mayor on funding certain positions year after year and why she's made those decisions.

618
00:50:15,290 --> 00:50:30,430
[SPEAKER_10]: But in this case, using free cash to fund the affordable housing trust is a recommended way of funding that trust it is it is something something cities are supposed to do periodically is to put money from free cash.

619
00:50:31,151 --> 00:50:39,593
[SPEAKER_10]: as well as other revenue streams like fractional incentives, linkage fees, the community, the CPA.

620
00:50:40,513 --> 00:50:46,255
[SPEAKER_10]: So yeah, this is definitely one of the revenue streams that should be fed into the Affordable Housing Trust.

621
00:50:46,275 --> 00:50:50,916
[SPEAKER_10]: So I think it is, again, I understand where everybody's coming from.

622
00:50:51,016 --> 00:50:59,258
[SPEAKER_10]: I personally support putting it forward tonight just to avoid politicizing what should be very routine matter.

623
00:50:59,798 --> 00:51:00,098
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

624
00:51:01,311 --> 00:51:01,751
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

625
00:51:01,972 --> 00:51:04,333
[SPEAKER_11]: And I actually, you know, don't think this is politicizing.

626
00:51:04,373 --> 00:51:13,981
[SPEAKER_11]: I think we have a routine for free cash expenditures, which is we get a free cash paper at the end of the fiscal year that contains all the allocations of free cash before it reverts to unusable on June 30th.

627
00:51:14,522 --> 00:51:17,244
[SPEAKER_10]: And while I support politicizing might've been a poor vocabulary.

628
00:51:17,744 --> 00:51:17,984
[SPEAKER_10]: Sorry.

629
00:51:18,165 --> 00:51:18,645
[SPEAKER_11]: That's okay.

630
00:51:19,165 --> 00:51:22,088
[SPEAKER_11]: I just, I support this a hundred percent love the work that you're doing.

631
00:51:22,248 --> 00:51:27,372
[SPEAKER_11]: I don't understand if you guys are saying you don't need it now and you could take it in four weeks, why it wasn't in the whole,

632
00:51:27,832 --> 00:51:28,994
[SPEAKER_11]: in the paper where we get all of it.

633
00:51:29,154 --> 00:51:30,695
[SPEAKER_11]: And so it's really not about you guys at all.

634
00:51:32,958 --> 00:51:34,780
[SPEAKER_11]: It's really just more about understanding like.

635
00:51:36,580 --> 00:51:40,121
[SPEAKER_11]: We, you know, for a long time we had no stabilization funds.

636
00:51:40,201 --> 00:51:41,622
[SPEAKER_11]: Now we have stabilization funds.

637
00:51:41,662 --> 00:51:48,444
[SPEAKER_11]: We've been regularly appropriating stabilization funds for a number of purposes at our meetings all the time.

638
00:51:49,445 --> 00:51:56,567
[SPEAKER_11]: Use of free cash to me, there's basically should be two purposes, which is to either hold it as free cash or put it into a fund.

639
00:51:57,928 --> 00:52:02,549
[SPEAKER_11]: This is obviously put it into the Affordable Housing Trust Fund, but I don't, there's a $21 million balance.

640
00:52:04,270 --> 00:52:06,991
[SPEAKER_11]: I don't know if we're going to put any of it into a stabilization fund.

641
00:52:07,131 --> 00:52:07,831
[SPEAKER_11]: I don't know how much.

642
00:52:08,031 --> 00:52:12,052
[SPEAKER_11]: And we're in kind of a budget situation where there are going to be competing priorities.

643
00:52:12,112 --> 00:52:23,456
[SPEAKER_11]: And I would like to see the full list of all the things that we're planning to use free cash to cover because maybe it's something we do in six months and not now if it means we fund something else.

644
00:52:23,556 --> 00:52:27,937
[SPEAKER_11]: And so that's just really kind of the conversation I want to have more knowledge about in terms

645
00:52:28,697 --> 00:52:30,638
[SPEAKER_11]: the standard process for expending free cash.

646
00:52:30,698 --> 00:52:32,099
[SPEAKER_11]: So that's me.

647
00:52:32,159 --> 00:52:53,954
[SPEAKER_11]: It sounds like a couple colleagues are of a different mind, so we'll have a motion and a vote or something, but I hope you can take away from sitting here till 9 o'clock that we all support your work and want to fund the Affordable Housing Trust and that actually it's not really about the information you could provide, but how this appropriation fits into the larger context of our use of free cash each year.

648
00:52:55,114 --> 00:52:55,715
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you guys.

649
00:52:56,636 --> 00:52:56,896
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

650
00:52:57,256 --> 00:52:57,617
[SPEAKER_11]: Who knows?

651
00:52:58,357 --> 00:53:00,279
[SPEAKER_11]: It looks like we're even on this one.

