[SPEAKER_11]: Yes 70 affirmative none the negative the motion passes and we have now the 26-104.

985
01:12:40,063 --> 01:12:45,147
[SPEAKER_11]: And if we could make Director O'Connor a co-host please adoption of updated hazard mitigation plan 2025.

986
01:12:46,901 --> 01:12:48,242
[SPEAKER_11]: Submitted by Mayor Brandon Hearn.

987
01:12:48,282 --> 01:12:56,429
[SPEAKER_11]: Dear President Beres and City Councilors, I respect the request and recommend your audible body approve the enclosed resolution adopting the City of Medford Hazard Mitigation Plan 2025 update.

988
01:12:56,449 --> 01:12:57,750
[SPEAKER_11]: This is a lengthy process.

989
01:12:57,790 --> 01:13:08,359
[SPEAKER_11]: There was a lengthy process relating to this plan, but only one round of review and revisions were required by both MEMA, Massachusetts Emergency Management Agency, and Federal Emergency Management Agency, FEMA, after the initial draft was submitted in January 2026.

990
01:13:09,440 --> 01:13:11,881
[SPEAKER_11]: The final revised plan was submitted to MEMA April 15th.

991
01:13:12,061 --> 01:13:19,142
[SPEAKER_11]: It received FEMA approval, pending adoption on May 6th with final approval of the plan this year, but we will not have to renew the plan again until 2030.

992
01:13:19,242 --> 01:13:23,543
[SPEAKER_11]: Final approval allows us to move forward with applications for federal grant funds that allow for mitigation projects.

993
01:13:24,463 --> 01:13:29,864
[SPEAKER_11]: A copy is sent earlier via email on April 15th and is available on the city's website.

994
01:13:29,944 --> 01:13:32,705
[SPEAKER_11]: Health Director, Marianne O'Connor, will be in attendance to address any questions.

995
01:13:33,145 --> 01:13:34,985
[SPEAKER_11]: Respectfully submitted, Brianna Lingle, current mayor.

996
01:13:35,106 --> 01:13:36,026
[SPEAKER_11]: Hi, Director O'Connor.

997
01:13:36,066 --> 01:13:36,946
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you for being here.

998
01:13:38,307 --> 01:13:46,494
[SPEAKER_11]: If you want to tell us a little bit more about the plan and we will adopt, you know, we'll take a vote formally on the resolution that was included.

999
01:13:46,574 --> 01:13:50,557
[SPEAKER_11]: I'm not going to read that out loud, but it is in the record and it is what we will submit.

1000
01:13:51,438 --> 01:13:51,838
[SPEAKER_01]: Terrific.

1001
01:13:51,878 --> 01:13:52,238
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you.

1002
01:13:52,258 --> 01:13:54,120
[SPEAKER_01]: Good evening, President Villescaz and City Councilors.

1003
01:13:54,620 --> 01:14:02,967
[SPEAKER_01]: I am here tonight to respectfully request and recommend that your Honorable Body adopt the City of Medford's Hazard Mitigation Plan 2025 update.

1004
01:14:05,828 --> 01:14:12,911
[SPEAKER_01]: I know I sent it to you all and it is a lengthy plan and I do appreciate your time reviewing it.

1005
01:14:12,931 --> 01:14:20,034
[SPEAKER_01]: The process was long, over a year and a half, but I believe the plan is really informative.

1006
01:14:20,394 --> 01:14:25,356
[SPEAKER_01]: I think it's laid out in an easy to read format and it is very comprehensive.

1007
01:14:27,072 --> 01:14:32,235
[SPEAKER_01]: So the hazard mitigation plan is basically required by the Federal Disaster Mitigation Act of 2000.

1008
01:14:34,036 --> 01:14:41,501
[SPEAKER_01]: It's a five-year roadmap for reducing impacts of hazards like floods, storms, and extreme weather.

1009
01:14:41,521 --> 01:14:52,648
[SPEAKER_01]: It highlights protections and projects and actions that the city can take ahead of time to reduce risks to human life and injury, as well as infrastructure.

1010
01:14:52,668 --> 01:14:55,669
[SPEAKER_01]: And it's basically there to help

1011
01:14:57,852 --> 01:15:00,474
[SPEAKER_01]: minimize loss and damage from natural disasters.

1012
01:15:01,195 --> 01:15:08,960
[SPEAKER_01]: We are required to do this by FEMA in order to receive federal funding going forward for any mitigation projects.

1013
01:15:09,801 --> 01:15:16,686
[SPEAKER_01]: The good news is once this is approved and adopted, we do not have to revisit it again until 2030.

1014
01:15:19,331 --> 01:15:25,753
[SPEAKER_01]: The approval of funding, so this is an update to the 2017 plan, which you're like, well, that's not five years.

1015
01:15:26,914 --> 01:15:34,596
[SPEAKER_01]: The little thing called COVID happened in between, but also we did actually receive approval for funding to move forward with this in 2022.

1016
01:15:35,737 --> 01:15:41,178
[SPEAKER_01]: We just did not actually receive the funding until close to 2024.

1017
01:15:41,338 --> 01:15:44,440
[SPEAKER_01]: So that's why it's been such a delay as well.

1018
01:15:45,040 --> 01:15:48,621
[SPEAKER_01]: But a big part of this whole plan was really community engagement.

1019
01:15:49,870 --> 01:16:09,381
[SPEAKER_01]: We went out there, we did surveys, we did community meetings, we had what we called conversation groups, and those were basically with community-based organizations like the Senior Center, the Walnut Street Center, West Medford Community Center, the Family Network folks.

1020
01:16:10,321 --> 01:16:12,062
[SPEAKER_01]: So we did a lot of outreach.

1021
01:16:12,102 --> 01:16:16,705
[SPEAKER_01]: We did also several community meetings where we gathered input as well.

1022
01:16:17,245 --> 01:16:25,987
[SPEAKER_01]: And I think if you look at the end of the plan, it's a lot of information about what folks were concerned about and what their comments were and what we tried to address.

1023
01:16:26,087 --> 01:16:31,648
[SPEAKER_01]: So I really am proud of the community engagement that we did.

1024
01:16:31,668 --> 01:16:45,530
[SPEAKER_01]: Really what the residents did emphasize was the need for financial supports, including home improvements to prepare for hazards, reliable emergency communications, especially for people with limited English literacy,

1025
01:16:46,350 --> 01:16:57,102
[SPEAKER_01]: stronger neighborhood support systems for seniors, caregivers, and people with chronic health conditions, and better coordination between city and trusted community-based organizations.

1026
01:16:58,467 --> 01:17:02,070
[SPEAKER_01]: So we took all of that into consideration as we were doing the plan.

1027
01:17:02,971 --> 01:17:06,393
[SPEAKER_01]: So FEMA is pretty prescriptive as to what we have to include in the plan.

1028
01:17:07,334 --> 01:17:17,982
[SPEAKER_01]: But some of what we did as far as our natural hazards include flooding events, storm events, extreme temperature, geological hazards.

1029
01:17:20,118 --> 01:17:29,907
[SPEAKER_01]: And, you know, the geological hazards probably are the lowest risks because they include like brush fire, brush fires, droughts, earthquakes and landslides.

1030
01:17:30,868 --> 01:17:38,975
[SPEAKER_01]: But, you know, the most common for us would be droughts, of course, because it streams out water supplies, but our highest risks are really the flooding events.

1031
01:17:39,876 --> 01:17:45,663
[SPEAKER_01]: We've had several of those over the past years, and storm events are moderate to risk as well.

1032
01:17:46,404 --> 01:17:52,210
[SPEAKER_01]: So like winter storms with disrupt power, and you know Northeasterners and, and that kind of thing.

1033
01:17:53,042 --> 01:18:02,224
[SPEAKER_01]: We don't see tornadoes typically here but we have known in the past few years they have kind of come about in local areas.

1034
01:18:04,065 --> 01:18:10,046
[SPEAKER_01]: So I think you know I certainly don't want to go through the 200 page plan.

1035
01:18:10,226 --> 01:18:16,288
[SPEAKER_01]: But if you have questions, I guess I just would point that the real need of the plan is probably around

1036
01:18:17,125 --> 01:18:22,671
[SPEAKER_01]: page 167 with our new updated hazard mitigation goals.

1037
01:18:23,351 --> 01:18:30,839
[SPEAKER_01]: And also, you know, in there as well as the status of our previous mitigation goals from our 2017 plan.

1038
01:18:31,620 --> 01:18:33,061
[SPEAKER_01]: And most of those were actually met.

1039
01:18:33,361 --> 01:18:39,047
[SPEAKER_01]: And if they weren't met, they were deprioritized because they were no longer deemed as

1040
01:18:40,268 --> 01:18:42,470
[SPEAKER_01]: being, you know, important or necessary.

1041
01:18:43,311 --> 01:18:58,125
[SPEAKER_01]: So I'm proud to say that most of that was done, but we did find kind of a gap in the way those 2017 mitigation goals were put forth, like they were more done like limited and departmental areas or silos.

1042
01:18:58,786 --> 01:19:04,632
[SPEAKER_01]: And so what we're proposing going forward with this plan is to really kind of bring in a group or a team

1043
01:19:05,380 --> 01:19:17,634
[SPEAKER_01]: of community mitigation, hazard mitigation folks, and to really work on this going forward as a team, and making sure that we're not just operating in silos.

1044
01:19:17,734 --> 01:19:20,997
[SPEAKER_01]: So I think that's important.

1045
01:19:22,278 --> 01:19:27,160
[SPEAKER_01]: But yeah, I'm happy to take any questions or any more thoughts.

1046
01:19:27,660 --> 01:19:38,704
[SPEAKER_01]: I think you will find the response to some of the public comment period towards the end of the plan, at the very end of the plan, is very interesting and informative.

1047
01:19:39,344 --> 01:19:41,105
[SPEAKER_01]: So I invite you to look at that.

1048
01:19:42,605 --> 01:19:45,946
[SPEAKER_01]: But certainly, you know, get to answer any questions.

1049
01:19:46,326 --> 01:19:47,947
[SPEAKER_01]: And thank you.

1050
01:19:49,902 --> 01:19:50,942
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you, Director O'Connor.

1051
01:19:50,982 --> 01:19:53,443
[SPEAKER_11]: Do we have any questions on the hazard mitigation plan?

1052
01:19:56,144 --> 01:19:56,924
[SPEAKER_11]: Vice President Lazaro.

1053
01:19:59,465 --> 01:20:00,306
[SPEAKER_13]: I have no questions.

1054
01:20:00,886 --> 01:20:02,346
[SPEAKER_13]: I appreciate the presentation.

1055
01:20:02,786 --> 01:20:08,988
[SPEAKER_13]: And to be honest, I trust Marianne O'Connor with my life and most of my possessions.

1056
01:20:09,289 --> 01:20:10,709
[SPEAKER_13]: So, motion to approve.

1057
01:20:13,490 --> 01:20:13,810
[SPEAKER_11]: Most.

1058
01:20:13,930 --> 01:20:14,690
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

1059
01:20:20,545 --> 01:20:24,948
[SPEAKER_11]: Marion, do you know which ones she doesn't trust you with?

1060
01:20:25,449 --> 01:20:26,189
[SPEAKER_01]: I appreciate it.

1061
01:20:26,770 --> 01:20:30,072
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you very much.

1062
01:20:30,653 --> 01:20:30,973
[SPEAKER_11]: All right.

1063
01:20:31,233 --> 01:20:36,897
[SPEAKER_11]: On the motion of Vice President Lazaro to approve seconded by seconded by Councilor Kelly.

1064
